tor in 1901, retiring December 26, 1903 as a Rear Admiral. His official accounts across four decades are recorded as among the most complete and accurate ever received by the Naval Department."},{"number":2,"category":"military","header":"Served on the Polaris expedition to the Arctic","body":"Thompson sailed on the Polaris Search Expedition to the Arctic and later brought survivors of the Virginius massacre from Santiago de Cuba to New York aboard a Navy vessel. He also served on the battleship Massachusetts to the close of the Spanish-American War."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Son of a minister; grandson of the Governor","body":"Theodore Strong Thompson was the son of Rev. Augustus Thompson, fifty-nine-year pastor of Eliot Congregational Church in Roxbury, and the grandson of Governor Caleb Strong of Massachusetts — one of the most prominent Federalist politicians of the early republic. The Rear Admiral thus carried both pastoral and gubernatorial lineage."}],"naming_inspiration":[],"quotes":[],"documents":[],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM098"},"residence":{"country":"United States"},"sources":[{"short":"EH 1909","page":"EH 1909"}],"research_sources":[],"slug":"theodore-thompson-1842"},"H04224":{"id":"H04224","is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"former_ids":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Martha Allen Thompson","first_name":"Martha","middle_name":"Allen","last_name":"Thompson","married_names":[]},"gender":"female","birth":{"year":1843,"month":12,"day":24,"city":"Roxbury","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1910},"baptism":{},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"generation_from_thomas":9,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_paths_to_thomas":1,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"H02673","mother_id":"I01218"},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notabl